 real inflation-adjusted spending, which rises 42.2 percent, from 2015 to 2024."></div>
      <div class="chart-legend">
        <span class="lg"><span class="sw nom"></span>Nominal (raw dollars)</span>
        <span class="lg"><span class="sw real"></span>Real (2015 dollars)</span>
        <span class="lg"><span class="sw pc"></span>Real per resident</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="sp-h">Where did the real increase go?</h3>
    <p>Almost all of it went to one place. Of the real spending growth between 2015 and 2024, about <b>83%</b> went to <b>public safety</b>, the Sheriff's Office, Fire and Rescue, and the Medical Examiner. Several other categories actually <b>shrank</b> in real terms over the same period, including general government, economic and physical environment, and interest on debt. This is the same pattern the budget shows today: new money has gone to policing and fire for a larger population, not to broad expansion of government.</p>

    <div class="chart-card">
      <h4 class="chart-title">Real (inflation-adjusted) change by category, 2015 to 2024</h4>
      <div id="chartCats" class="chart-svg" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart of real spending change by category from 2015 to 2024. Public safety up 76 percent, transportation up 91 percent, human services up 80 percent, culture and recreation up 48 percent, general government down 46 percent, economic and physical environment down 28 percent, interest on debt down 66 percent."></div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <h3>How this relates to the tax debate</h3>
      <p>Adjusted for inflation and population, real spending per resident grew about 22% over the nine-year period, and most of the real growth went to public safety. Readers can weigh how these figures bear on claims that rising home values have produced surplus revenue. Any reduction in property tax revenue would apply to this budget as it stands.</p>
